\f3\i\b \cf0 \
Eibar
\f0\i0\b0 .  Eibar is the language spoken by most huum and huum-appearing residents of Saskantinon of whatever genetic mix, who live north of the River 
\f2\i Setta
\f0\i0  and east of Kahilakol, and with the exception of Kahilabequa and Byenung, where Eibar is common but Sogomsh is more pervasive.  It is the most widely spoken language in Saskantinon.
\fs24 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardeftab720\li360\sl288\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\fs26 \cf0 \
It is the native language of the northern and western regions. As the official language of the Helioptic scribes it is the language of power in the region.  While it is not the first language of Byenung, many of the residents of that province, especially those involved in jurisprudence, are experts at it and may speak (and write) it even better than, say, a rural farmer from Rutonijal or a rancher from Jiv\'e1kala. 
\fs24 \

\fs26 \
The standard accent of Eibar is that of the province of Eibar, one of the earliest settlements of Bar speaking huum in the region. Their pronunciation and idioms became the norm.  But as the centuries passed, Eibar itself became considerably more diverse, absorbing immigrants from Wesshewen, Ilyushan, Krbshanana and places even further away. These days, it is not unusual to hear all kinds of Eibar accents in Eibar itself, including Eibarq. 
\fs24 \

\fs26 \
The other Eibar-speaking areas of Saskantinon have regional accents. In most cases minor variations in sounds and a few idiomatic words. The ones that come close to full-fledged dialects are spoken in the remote hills and valleys of Eelan, the Weir Lands and Oknott.
\fs24 \

